panel_pds.text: The principal display surface is the main area of a food container or package visible under normal sale or use. Under both the SFCR and FDR, it is usually the visible surface (excluding the top), the lid if that is most visible, or 40% of the container if no single surface is visible. Special rules apply for bags, wine containers, wrappers, or when labels must be on tags. “Readily discernible” means label information must be easy to see and read by an ordinary person under normal conditions

The principal display surface is the main area of a food container or package visible under normal sale or use. Under both the SFCR and FDR, it is usually the visible surface (excluding the top), the lid if that is most visible, or 40% of the container if no single surface is visible. Special rules apply for bags, wine containers, wrappers, or when labels must be on tags. “Readily discernible” means label information must be easy to see and read by an ordinary person under normal conditions

panel_pdp.text: The principal display panel (PDP) is the part of a food label most visible under normal sale or use. Under the SFCR, it is generally the label on the main visible surface of the container, with specific rules for display cards, ornamental containers, non-consumer prepackaged foods, and unpackaged foods. Under the FDR, consumer prepackaged foods follow the SFCR definition, while other prepackaged or unpackaged foods use the visible container or food surface (excluding the bottom).
